Q4¶

Convert the columns with data type "object" to "category" using bracket notation.¶

Convert the columns with data type "object" to "category" using dot notation.¶

In [20]:
## Convert using bracket notation

WorldBank["country"] = WorldBank["country"].astype("category")
WorldBank["continent"] = WorldBank["continent"].astype("category")

## Convert using dot notation

WorldBank.country = WorldBank.country.astype("category")
WorldBank.continent = WorldBank.continent.astype("category")

Q23¶

Create a new column that is the log of the gdpPercap column and create a scatter plot (with matplotlib, seaborn, or altair) with log of gdp on the x-axis and life expectancy on the y-axis. Drawing on this plot and the result from #25, write a paragraph explaining your results and some potential explanations for the relationship or lack thereof.¶

In [150]:
WorldBank['log_gdpPercap'] = np.log(WorldBank['gdpPercap'])
In [152]:
# plot log of gdpPercap on the x-axis and life expectancy on the y-axis.
sns.scatterplot(WorldBank, 
                x = "log_gdpPercap",
                y = "lifeExp");

Drawing on this plot and the result from #25, write a paragraph explaining your results and some potential explanations for the relationship or lack thereof.¶

From the scatterplot from Q23, there is a relationship between the log of gdpPercap and lifeExp, as we can see the relationship between both quantitative variables is a positive relationship that is increasing as log of gdpPercap increases, lifeExp increases in comparision. The relationship between each of the continents is not made as apparent due to the fact that we do not colorcode the scatterplot by the column 'continent'. We see that for the scatterplot created in Q25, the slopes are still positive but each slope for specific countries are more steeper than others. For example, in the scatterplot of Q25, from pure observation the slope of Europe is steeper than the slope of Asia. In Q25, the relationship between log gdpPercap and lifeExp is made clearer for each specific continent than Q23.

Q24¶

Create another scatterplot (with matplotlib, seaborn, or altair) with log of gdp and life expectancy and color the points by continent.¶

In [157]:
# plot log of gdpPercap on the x-axis and life expectancy on the y-axis.
sns.scatterplot(WorldBank, 
                x = "log_gdpPercap",
                y = "lifeExp",
                hue = "continent");
Q25¶

Create a scatterplot with altair with log of gdp and life expectancy, color the points by continent, add tooltip functionality so that hovering over the data points will show the continent, country, and year of that data point, and add a title.¶

In [162]:
# Plot log of gdpPercap and life expectancy 

alt.Chart(WorldBank).mark_circle().encode(
    x = "log_gdpPercap",
    y = "lifeExp")
Out[162]:
In [164]:
# Add color by continent and title
alt.Chart(WorldBank).mark_circle().encode(
    x = "log_gdpPercap",
    y = "lifeExp",
    color = "continent"). \
    properties(title = "Log GDP Per Capita vs Life Expectancy").interactive()
Out[164]:
In [165]:
# Add color by continent, title, and tooltip
alt.Chart(WorldBank).mark_circle().encode(

    properties(title = "Log GDP Per Capita vs Life Expectancy").interactive()
